/*
    Strategy D: chain bindings via multiple polymorphic calls so that
    a row var gets indirectly bound to a row containing itself.

    apply1 binds its e to <io | e'>  (via call inside body with io effect)
    apply2 binds its e to <io | e''>
    ...

    Actually: the simplest way to recurse via subst chains.

    apply2 takes Fn() <..e> i32 (row var x).
    Inside, apply2 calls apply2 itself — recursion. Each call instantiates
    a fresh x'. Then apply2's body is Fn() <..e> i32, which we pass as
    the arg. x' (callee fresh) unifies with x (outer signature).
    Then body row of apply2 is <..x'> which has been bound to <..x>.
    Then signature gate unifies <..x> with declared <..e>=<..x>.

    All var-to-var. Still no cycle...

    Let's try passing apply2 itself as the fn — but apply2 has wrong arity.

    What if we use the handle expression — fresh residual_var μ that's
    bound to something containing μ via a clause's body? Try handle.
*/

io :: pub effect
    log :: fn(msg: []const u8) i32

apply :: pub fn(f: Fn() <..e> i32) <..e> i32
    f()

// Self-referential: g is Fn taking nothing returning Fn() <..e> i32.
// We then call apply(g()) — apply expects Fn() <..e> i32, g() returns
// Fn() <..e> i32. Should be fine.
weird :: pub fn(g: Fn() Fn() <..e> i32) <..e> i32
    apply(g())
